bution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","(Devon): topographic name from Middle English <i>thorning</i> ‘dweller by a thorn bush’, from Middle English <i>thorn</i> + <i>-ing</i> ‘man’, a type of locative formation peculiar to Devon.","perhaps also a habitational name from either of two places called Thurning (in Northamptonshire and Norfolk), probably derived from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ + the groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>, or from <i>thorning</i> ‘thorny place’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ALICE","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"MRS","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Latin <i>Ursus</i> ‘bear’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"*E ALICE MRS William THIRNING was born in 1252, in England, United Kingdom. She married William Thirning about 1275, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1252–":"1252–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1276–1330":"1276–1330","1252–Female":"1252–Surnud","1276":"1276","1330":"1330","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","about 1275":"umbes 1275","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1252–":"1252–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1276–1330":"1276–1330","1252–Female":"1252–Kuollut","1276":"1276","1330":"1330","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","about 1275":"noin 1275","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1252–":"1252–Décédée","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1276–1330":"1276–1330","1252–Female":"1252–Décédée","1276":"1276","1330":"1330","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","about 1275":"environ 1275","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"*E ALICE MRS William THIRNING est née en 1252, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé William Thirning environ 1275, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée à Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"1252–":"1252–Verstorben","1250–Male":"1250–Verstorben","1276–1330":"1276–1330","1252–Female":"1252–Verstorben","1276":"1276","1330":"1330","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","about 1275":"um 1275","Engla